    <section class="funFacts padding-block-700">
        <h2 class="fs-secondary-heading">Fun Facts</h2>
        <ul class="regular-list">
            <li>
                Eucalyptus is a diverse genus, comprising over 700 species. It
                is known for its impressive variety of forms, including tall
                trees, mallee shrubs, and even eucalyptus species that resemble
                small bushes
            </li>
            <li>
                Many eucalyptus species have adaptations that help them survive
                and even benefit from wildfires. They have thick, fibrous bark
                that can withstand intense heat, and some species produce seeds
                that germinate after a fire, taking advantage of the cleared
                landscape.
            </li>
            <li>
                Eucalyptus trees are known for their fast growth rates. Some
                species can grow several feet per year, making them one of the
                fastest-growing tree genera.
            </li>
            <li>
                Indigenous Australians have long used eucalyptus leaves for
                various medicinal purposes. They would crush the leaves and use
                them as poultices for treating wounds, respiratory ailments, and
                other conditions.
            </li>
        </ul>
